According to tradition and the Vaishnava point of view, the god on the hill ([[Tirupati]]) had parted with his conch and the [[Sudarshana chakra]] to Karun<U+0101>kara Perum<U+0101>l, the conqueror of [[Kalinga]] and the true hero of the [[Kalingathuparani]]<ref name="Ancient India: collected essays on the literary and political history of Southern India, page 215">''Ancient India: collected essays on the literary and political history of Southern India, page 215''</ref>. Karunakara Thondaiman will defeat the Kalinga armies of Anantavarman and plant a pillar of victory in Kalinga (modern day [[Orissa]]). Anantavarman will flee never to be found again<ref>''Sri Varadarajaswami Temple, Kanchi: A Study of Its History, Art and Architecture'', page 13.</ref>. The war is described by [[Jayamkondar]], the poet-laureate of [[Kulottunga Chola I]] in graphic detail in the poem ''[[Kalinkkattuparani]]''. Here is an excerpt:

<center>

''Having thus laid waste the whole of the sea-coast kingdom of Kalinga, and planting there a pillar of victory,<br> Karunakara Thondaiman, the lord of Vandaiyar, returns and lays at the feet of his master all the spoils of war''<ref>''Studies in Tamil Literature and History'', page 258</ref>

</center>

Vandaiyar, now identified with Vandalur is an area in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]<ref>''Ancient India: collected essays on the literary and political history of Southern India'', page 146</ref>

